spec: concurrent_futures_extra158
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(concurrent.futures)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/concurrent.futures.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/concurrent.futures.html — Python concurrent.futures module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/concurrent/futures/_base.py"
  notes:
    - "This spec covers: concurrent.futures._base.Executor class identity (name, module, base) and __dict__ membership checks (submit, map, __enter__, __exit__). concurrent.futures._base.Executor.__name__=='Executor' (len=8: 'E'+'x'+'e'+'c'+'u'+'t'+'o'+'r'=8); concurrent.futures._base.Executor.__module__=='concurrent.futures._base' (len=24: 'concurrent'=10+'.'=1+'futures'=7+'.'=1+'_base'=5=24; Executor lives in the private _base submodule, NOT at the top level of concurrent.futures); concurrent.futures._base.Executor.__bases__[0].__name__=='object' (Executor inherits directly from object — it is the abstract root of the executor hierarchy; neither ThreadPoolExecutor nor ProcessPoolExecutor are bases); Executor.__dict__.__contains__('submit')==True; Executor.__dict__.__contains__('map')==True; Executor.__dict__.__contains__('__enter__')==True; Executor.__dict__.__contains__('__exit__')==True. All verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "concurrent.futures._base.Executor.__module__=='concurrent.futures._base' (len=24) — accessing Executor via the private _base submodule gives the same class as concurrent.futures.Executor; the _base submodule is the actual implementation file (Lib/concurrent/futures/_base.py); 'concurrent.futures._base' (len=24: 'concurrent'=10+'.'=1+'futures'=7+'.'=1+'_base'=5=24); compare: concurrent.futures.Executor.__module__=='concurrent.futures._base' (same len=24; whether accessed via the top-level package or the _base submodule, Executor.__module__ is always 'concurrent.futures._base'). Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "Executor.__dict__.__contains__ checks — Executor.__dict__.__contains__('submit')==True (Executor defines submit() as an abstract method that raises NotImplementedError); Executor.__dict__.__contains__('map')==True (Executor provides a concrete map() implementation using submit()); Executor.__dict__.__contains__('__enter__')==True (Executor.__enter__ returns self for context manager use); Executor.__dict__.__contains__('__exit__')==True (Executor.__exit__ calls shutdown(wait=True)); Executor.__dict__.__contains__('shutdown')==True (Executor defines a shutdown() method); all four methods specified in the task are present in Executor.__dict__ directly (not inherited). Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "concurrent.futures._base.Executor.__bases__[0].__name__=='object' — Executor inherits directly from object; it is the abstract root class of the executor hierarchy; concrete subclasses are ThreadPoolExecutor (in concurrent.futures.thread) and ProcessPoolExecutor (in concurrent.futures.process); Executor.__bases__[0].__name__=='object' confirms that Executor has no asyncio or other framework dependency — it is a standalone pure Python abstract base class; note: Executor does NOT use abc.ABCMeta; submit() raises NotImplementedError conventionally rather than being decorated with @abstractmethod. Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

